# Styling

## CSS modules — BEM only

Name every class with **BEM**. The block name matches the component (kebab-case, same as the file stem).

| Part | Pattern | Example |
|------|---------|---------|
| Block | `.block` | `.site-header` |
| Element | `.block__element` | `.site-header__brand` |
| Modifier | `.block--modifier`, `.block__element--modifier` | `.site-header--dark` |

Apply modifiers on the element in JSX — do not encode state with nested selectors.

## Specificity 0,1,0 — classes only

Every selector must be **a single BEM class** (specificity `0,1,0`).

```css
/* ✅ one class */
.site-header__brand { display: flex; }

/* ❌ element, descendant, or compound selectors */
.hero-teaser__play svg { width: 26px; }
.site-logo--dark .site-logo__mark { width: 1.75rem; }
```

Never target HTML elements (`svg`, `img`, `a`, etc.). Give each styled node its own BEM class. Pseudo-classes on the same class (`:hover`, `:focus-visible`) are allowed.

Put modifiers on the child in TSX, not via parent selectors in CSS:

```tsx
className={clsx({
  [styles["site-logo__mark"]]: true,
  [styles["site-logo__mark--dark"]]: variant === "dark",
})}
```

## Bracket notation in TSX

Always access CSS module classes with **bracket notation**:

```tsx
className={styles["site-header"]}
className={clsx({
  [styles["site-header"]]: true,
  [styles["site-header--dark"]]: variant === "dark",
})}
```

## Rem vs em vs px

- **`rem`** — typography: `font-size`, `line-height`, `letter-spacing`, spacing between text
- **`em`** — media query breakpoints only (divide px by 16: `768px` → `48em`)
- **`px`** — presentational layout: padding, margins, `border-radius`, borders, outlines

Do not use `px` or `rem` in `@media` width/height conditions.

Quick check: text reads → `rem`; layout reflow → `em`; box looks → `px`.

## clsx

One style per call: **object notation** for conditionals, **array notation** for plain concatenation. Do not mix string args with `&&` conditionals or with object notation.

```tsx
// ✅ conditionals
className={clsx(
  {
    [styles["site-logo"]]: true,
    [styles["site-logo--dark"]]: variant === "dark",
  },
  classNames,
)}

// ✅ concatenation only
className={clsx([styles["site-logo"], classNames])}

// ❌ && conditionals or string + object mix
className={clsx(styles["site-logo"], variant === "dark" && styles["site-logo--dark"])}
```

When a component accepts `classNames`, pass it as a trailing argument after the object.
